past year.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about hormonal changes in menopause is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oestrone becomes the major circulating oestrogen","Follicle stimulating hormone levels decrease","Ovarian testosterone production increases","Oestradiol remains the dominant oestrogen","Adrenal androgen production ceases"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring menopause, \u003Cstrong\u003Eoestrone\u003C/strong\u003E becomes the major circulating oestrogen, primarily produced through peripheral aromatization of androgens in adipose tissue. This is in contrast to the reproductive years when \u003Cstrong\u003Eoestradiol\u003C/strong\u003E is the dominant oestrogen produced by the ovaries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFollicle stimulating hormone levels\u003C/strong\u003E actually increase markedly during menopause due to the loss of negative feedback from declining ovarian hormones. \u003Cstrong\u003EOvarian testosterone production\u003C/strong\u003E decreases during menopause, though not as dramatically as oestradiol. \u003Cstrong\u003EAdrenal androgen production\u003C/strong\u003E continues throughout menopause, although decreasing slightly with age, providing substrates for peripheral oestrogen production.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["After menopause, oestrone becomes the primary circulating oestrogen due to peripheral aromatization of androgens in adipose tissue","Follicle stimulating hormone levels increase markedly during menopause due to loss of negative feedback","Ovarian oestradiol production decreases significantly during menopause","Adrenal androgen production continues throughout menopause"],"references":["Okeke T, Anyaehie U, Ezenyeaku C. Premature menopause. Ann Med Health Sci Res. 2013 Jan;3(1):90-5. doi: 10.4103/2141-9248.109458. PMID: 23634337; PMCID: PMC3634232","Magraith K, Jang C. M